    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i don't really get the comparison. can you just explain the actual process? like, what happens if the seller refuses to move out or if there's an issue with the title during the escrow period?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! In the actual process, when you sign a contract to buy a house, you and the seller agree to meet certain conditions before the sale is finalized. This is where the escrow comes in—it's a neutral third party that holds the money you've paid for the house, as well as any other required funds, until the transaction is complete.\n\nIf the seller refuses to move out, the escrow company acts as a mediator. They ensure that the seller fulfills their obligations, like removing their belongings from the property and providing a clear title, before releasing your funds.\n\nIf there's an issue with the title, the escrow company will work with you and the seller to resolve the problem. This might involve obtaining title insurance, addressing any liens, or correcting discrepancies in the property's history. The goal is to make sure that the title is clear and that you can take ownership of the house without any legal troubles.\n\nThroughout this process, the escrow company is like a vigilant goblin, keeping a watchful eye on the transaction and making sure everything goes according to plan. They ensure that the house is yours once all the conditions are met, and then they release the funds to you, completing the magical transfer of ownership.",
